1
00:00:12,613 --> 00:00:14,548
(lightning strikes)

2
00:00:14,548 --> 00:00:18,319
(dramatic music)

3
00:00:32,600 --> 00:00:36,404
(sirens sound)

4
00:00:39,973 --> 00:00:43,677
(dramatic music)

5
00:01:03,397 --> 00:01:05,599
- [Man] He's heading
 across the field.

6
00:01:05,599 --> 00:01:09,170
(dramatic music)

7
00:01:28,822 --> 00:01:31,425
He's doubled back onto the road.

8
00:01:31,425 --> 00:01:33,394
Let's go.

9
00:01:33,394 --> 00:01:37,265
(dramatic music)

10
00:01:58,986 --> 00:02:02,656
(engine starts)

11
00:02:04,892 --> 00:02:08,862
(dramatic music)

12
00:03:22,570 --> 00:03:24,972
(train horn sounds)

13
00:03:24,972 --> 00:03:28,676
(dramatic music)

14
00:03:42,290 --> 00:03:45,259
(sirens sound)

15
00:04:07,481 --> 00:04:09,049
He's gotta be around
 here somewhere.

16
00:04:09,049 --> 00:04:10,484
Keep your eyes open.

17
00:04:10,484 --> 00:04:13,454
(bird calls)

18
00:04:20,594 --> 00:04:23,631
Ma'am.

19
00:04:23,631 --> 00:04:24,965
There's an escaped
 convict on the loose

20
00:04:24,965 --> 00:04:25,999
and we're pretty
 sure he came onto

21
00:04:25,999 --> 00:04:27,568
your property from the beach.

22
00:04:27,568 --> 00:04:29,136
He's a killer, lady.

23
00:04:29,136 --> 00:04:31,004
- I haven't seen anyone.

24
00:04:31,004 --> 00:04:33,441
But you're welcome
 to look around.

25
00:04:41,582 --> 00:04:45,218
(bird calls)

26
00:04:52,860 --> 00:04:56,430
(dramatic music)

27
00:05:05,138 --> 00:05:07,140
- What'd he do, bury himself?

28
00:05:07,140 --> 00:05:10,310
(dramatic music)

29
00:05:10,310 --> 00:05:12,480
Are you sure you haven't
seen anything, lady?

30
00:05:12,480 --> 00:05:15,849
(dramatic music)

31
00:05:15,849 --> 00:05:18,419
(bird calls)

32
00:05:20,421 --> 00:05:21,555
- I think I saw him.

33
00:05:21,555 --> 00:05:23,156
He's down there.

34
00:05:23,156 --> 00:05:26,694
(dramatic music)

35
00:05:27,661 --> 00:05:28,562
Hold it!

36
00:05:28,562 --> 00:05:30,330
Stop or I'll shoot!

37
00:05:30,330 --> 00:05:34,001
(dramatic music)

38
00:05:38,672 --> 00:05:40,574
- That wasn't very
 smart, Pascal.

39
00:05:40,574 --> 00:05:42,309
Come on, back to your cage.

40
00:05:42,309 --> 00:05:46,079
(dramatic music)

41
00:07:37,190 --> 00:07:38,892
- Take it easy now,
 you hear, Alex?

42
00:07:38,892 --> 00:07:40,127
- Likewise, buddy.

43
00:07:40,127 --> 00:07:41,028
- Don't worry, I'll see
you tomorrow morning.

44
00:07:41,028 --> 00:07:43,163
Come by about 10:00.

45
00:07:47,134 --> 00:07:50,270
(dog growling)

46
00:07:51,972 --> 00:07:55,776
(dog barking)

47
00:07:57,377 --> 00:07:59,379
- Hey, Bart, leave him alone.

48
00:07:59,379 --> 00:08:00,781
Down, boy, down.

49
00:08:00,781 --> 00:08:03,884
(dog barking)

50
00:08:03,884 --> 00:08:05,285
Come back here.

51
00:08:05,285 --> 00:08:06,854
Come on, come on,
 come back here.

52
00:08:06,854 --> 00:08:09,189
(bird calls)

53
00:08:09,189 --> 00:08:11,825
Well, well, well,
 if it isn't Lucille.

54
00:08:11,825 --> 00:08:12,926
What do you keep in that?

55
00:08:12,926 --> 00:08:14,562
Come on, remember old Michel?

56
00:08:14,562 --> 00:08:15,929
Or have I changed that much?

57
00:08:15,929 --> 00:08:17,364
- You're Michel?

58
00:08:17,364 --> 00:08:19,432
The Michel?

59
00:08:19,432 --> 00:08:22,570
- Now, now, I haven't seen
 you since uncle Andre's.

60
00:08:22,570 --> 00:08:24,638
Well you seem fine.

61
00:08:24,638 --> 00:08:26,774
It is

62
00:08:26,774 --> 00:08:28,008
Hey, who's the doll?

63
00:08:28,008 --> 00:08:30,077
- [Lucille] That uncle
 Andre's daughter.

64
00:08:30,077 --> 00:08:31,111
- [Michel] Falesse?

65
00:08:31,111 --> 00:08:32,179
(laughing)

66
00:08:32,179 --> 00:08:33,647
Well look at her.

67
00:08:33,647 --> 00:08:36,516
Why 13 years ago, you
 only came up to my elbow.

68
00:08:36,516 --> 00:08:38,318
I'm your cousin MIchel.

69
00:08:38,318 --> 00:08:39,620
The meanie.

70
00:08:39,620 --> 00:08:41,088
I always used to tease
 the pants off of you.

71
00:08:41,088 --> 00:08:42,355
Don't you remember?

72
00:08:42,355 --> 00:08:43,724
You used to yell, Michel!

73
00:08:43,724 --> 00:08:44,892
- Uh-uh.

74
00:08:44,892 --> 00:08:45,826
Who cares?

75
00:08:45,826 --> 00:08:46,594
Cousins are always welcome.

76
00:08:46,594 --> 00:08:47,360
- Get a kiss?

77
00:08:47,360 --> 00:08:48,228
- Of course.

78
00:08:48,228 --> 00:08:51,131
(laughing)

79
00:08:53,734 --> 00:08:55,068
- What brings you here, Michel?

80
00:08:55,068 --> 00:08:57,605
- Ah, I'm just passing
 through on business.

81
00:08:57,605 --> 00:08:59,372
But I travel a lot for
pleasure too, of course.

82
00:08:59,372 --> 00:09:00,608
(laughing)

83
00:09:00,608 --> 00:09:01,541
You know how it is
 when you get older,

84
00:09:01,541 --> 00:09:02,876
you get a little nostalgic.

85
00:09:02,876 --> 00:09:04,277
- Good morning, it
 looks like your dog's

86
00:09:04,277 --> 00:09:06,113
made himself right
 at home already.

87
00:09:06,113 --> 00:09:07,648
- Morning.

88
00:09:07,648 --> 00:09:09,750
Doesn't say too much for his
 master's manners, does it?

89
00:09:09,750 --> 00:09:10,918
(laughing)

90
00:09:10,918 --> 00:09:12,385
- [Lucille] Come on in, Michel.

91
00:09:12,385 --> 00:09:14,087
I see you don't recognize Colin.

92
00:09:14,087 --> 00:09:17,390
- Oh your son, no,
 he's pretty grown up.

93
00:09:19,059 --> 00:09:22,262
Here's to you, Andre.

94
00:09:24,097 --> 00:09:27,267
Ah he's truly a great
 man, you know that, Colin?

95
00:09:27,267 --> 00:09:28,602
- Sure.

96
00:09:28,602 --> 00:09:29,903
In his own way.

97
00:09:29,903 --> 00:09:32,606
- You were too young.

98
00:09:32,606 --> 00:09:35,508
Too young to really know him.

99
00:09:35,508 --> 00:09:39,146
After all, you were only
 five or six when it happened.

100
00:09:39,146 --> 00:09:41,715
- Colin was eight at the time.

101
00:09:41,715 --> 00:09:45,052
- Yep, little Colin was
just eight years old.

102
00:09:45,052 --> 00:09:46,920
Not very experienced
 but still old enough

103
00:09:46,920 --> 00:09:48,922
to remember how the
 supreme master Andre

104
00:09:48,922 --> 00:09:53,026
who had survived so many
of the squalls of life,

105
00:09:53,026 --> 00:09:54,795
ended up drowning like a rat.

106
00:09:54,795 --> 00:09:57,197
- Colin.

107
00:09:57,197 --> 00:09:58,365
You.

108
00:09:58,365 --> 00:10:01,234
(laughing)

109
00:10:01,234 --> 00:10:02,469
Don't talk about
 father like that,

110
00:10:02,469 --> 00:10:04,337
I won't permit it.

111
00:10:04,337 --> 00:10:06,473
- Why so sensitive, m'lady?

112
00:10:06,473 --> 00:10:09,810
What's important is you've
 inherited his fortune and us.

113
00:10:09,810 --> 00:10:12,846
Your underlings, who stand
 always to kiss your feet.

114
00:10:12,846 --> 00:10:16,449
(dramatic music)

115
00:10:17,918 --> 00:10:19,687
- [Lucille] Colin.

116
00:10:19,687 --> 00:10:23,423
(dramatic music)

117
00:10:28,128 --> 00:10:29,429
(laughing)

118
00:10:29,429 --> 00:10:30,864
I always warned him,
it was bound to get him

119
00:10:30,864 --> 00:10:32,933
sooner or later, didn't I?

120
00:10:32,933 --> 00:10:35,068
(dramatic music)

121
00:10:35,068 --> 00:10:37,137
- Sure.

122
00:10:37,137 --> 00:10:39,940
He loved to challenge the sea.

123
00:10:39,940 --> 00:10:42,609
To try to master it.

124
00:10:42,609 --> 00:10:45,078
He was a true sportsman.

125
00:10:45,078 --> 00:10:48,882
How we all admired him.

126
00:10:48,882 --> 00:10:52,786
Especially his
 daughter, Falesse.

127
00:10:52,786 --> 00:10:56,724
And then that morning, the
 coast guard got a report

128
00:10:56,724 --> 00:11:00,660
of a cabin cruiser
 adrift unmanned.

129
00:11:00,660 --> 00:11:02,930
Maybe the motor had broken down.

130
00:11:02,930 --> 00:11:06,299
And he'd made a desperate
 attempt to swim ashore.

131
00:11:06,299 --> 00:11:09,770
The sea had always been his
 idol and it became his tomb.

132
00:11:09,770 --> 00:11:13,640
(dramatic music)

133
00:11:20,580 --> 00:11:22,182
- [Man2] (Latin spoken)

134
00:11:22,182 --> 00:11:24,818
- [Colin] Amen.

135
00:11:27,988 --> 00:11:29,456
(laughing)

136
00:11:29,456 --> 00:11:32,159
- Well look at the sort of
 thing I carry around with me.

137
00:11:32,159 --> 00:11:35,428
A bunch of knickknacks,
like this number here.

138
00:11:35,428 --> 00:11:37,197
Why don't you try
 it on for size, huh?

139
00:11:37,197 --> 00:11:38,832
Picked it up at the
 fair, the phono fair,

140
00:11:38,832 --> 00:11:40,267
you know, in Copenhagen?

141
00:11:40,267 --> 00:11:41,735
You should see the
goodies they got there.

142
00:11:41,735 --> 00:11:43,236
- It's a living jewel.

143
00:11:43,236 --> 00:11:44,772
- Go on, put it on your arm.

144
00:11:44,772 --> 00:11:47,240
(laughing)

145
00:11:47,240 --> 00:11:48,608
How's it feel?

146
00:11:48,608 --> 00:11:50,277
Titillating, isn't it?

147
00:11:50,277 --> 00:11:51,945
A friend of mine
 went buggy over it.

148
00:11:51,945 --> 00:11:54,381
(laughing)

149
00:11:55,415 --> 00:11:57,150
- You're sweet.

150
00:11:57,150 --> 00:11:58,551
- Throw it in here.

151
00:11:58,551 --> 00:11:59,953
Kiki will be terribly tickeld.

152
00:11:59,953 --> 00:12:01,221
- Kiki?

153
00:12:01,221 --> 00:12:02,856
- And Kioko, we have two
vultures in the family.

154
00:12:02,856 --> 00:12:04,691
I'm trying to satisfy
 their appetite.

155
00:12:04,691 --> 00:12:07,360
Drives him to destruction.

156
00:12:07,360 --> 00:12:10,964
- They go for innards, feet,
 vertebrae, sacred bones.

157
00:12:10,964 --> 00:12:12,265
Real cuisine.

158
00:12:12,265 --> 00:12:14,334
(laughing)

159
00:12:16,036 --> 00:12:18,071
- To give a fellow like
that bones, you need

160
00:12:18,071 --> 00:12:20,307
a cemetery practically.

161
00:12:20,307 --> 00:12:21,574
- Practically.

162
00:12:21,574 --> 00:12:22,609
- You got one?

163
00:12:22,609 --> 00:12:25,412
Fascinated.

164
00:12:25,412 --> 00:12:28,181
- If you really want to see
 it, it's as good as done.

165
00:12:28,181 --> 00:12:31,284
- Good.

166
00:12:31,284 --> 00:12:32,519
- [Falesse] We found
 some Etruscan tombs

167
00:12:32,519 --> 00:12:33,787
right here on the ground.

168
00:12:33,787 --> 00:12:35,022
- [Michel] Any gold?

169
00:12:35,022 --> 00:12:36,156
- Nope, it had
 already been looted.

170
00:12:36,156 --> 00:12:37,090
There.

171
00:12:37,090 --> 00:12:38,125
(laughing)

172
00:12:38,125 --> 00:12:39,192
Think he'll get titillated?

173
00:12:39,192 --> 00:12:40,360
- Why not?

174
00:12:40,360 --> 00:12:41,428
(laughing)

175
00:12:41,428 --> 00:12:42,863
Get in there, titillate.

176
00:12:42,863 --> 00:12:44,297
(laughing)

177
00:12:44,297 --> 00:12:45,398
You know that skull
 looks like an old friend.

178
00:12:45,398 --> 00:12:46,934
(laughing)

179
00:12:46,934 --> 00:12:49,803
- Come on, what's happened
 to your great appetite?

180
00:12:49,803 --> 00:12:51,504
What is this, a hunger strike?

181
00:12:51,504 --> 00:12:55,042
Come on, take it.

182
00:12:55,042 --> 00:12:56,643
What's the matter?

183
00:12:56,643 --> 00:12:58,611
(dog barking)

184
00:12:58,611 --> 00:13:02,215
(dramatic music)

185
00:13:23,336 --> 00:13:26,206
(bird calls)

186
00:13:29,409 --> 00:13:33,246
(dramatic music)

187
00:13:35,983 --> 00:13:37,384
- Well uncle Alfans.

188
00:13:37,384 --> 00:13:41,054
(dog growling)

189
00:13:45,859 --> 00:13:49,362
(bird calls)

190
00:13:58,671 --> 00:14:00,673
(whistling)

191
00:14:02,109 --> 00:14:03,576
- It sounded like your dog
 was trembling with joy.

192
00:14:03,576 --> 00:14:05,278
I bet he's met a girlfriend.

193
00:14:05,278 --> 00:14:07,080
- Ah, he sure has
 a way with women.

194
00:14:07,080 --> 00:14:09,116
If I were half as successful.

195
00:14:09,116 --> 00:14:10,483
- At titillating?

196
00:14:10,483 --> 00:14:11,919
- Yeah.

197
00:14:11,919 --> 00:14:13,186
- [Falesse] Don't despair,
 Michel, the night's

198
00:14:13,186 --> 00:14:14,888
still young, you may
 have the same luck.

199
00:14:14,888 --> 00:14:18,225
(dramatic music)

200
00:14:18,225 --> 00:14:19,792
- A stroll in the moonlight?

201
00:14:19,792 --> 00:14:24,064
(dramatic music)

202
00:14:24,064 --> 00:14:26,967
How romantic.

203
00:14:26,967 --> 00:14:29,702
I'd be the last to
 want to interrupt you.

204
00:14:29,702 --> 00:14:31,538
I'll retire.

205
00:14:31,538 --> 00:14:33,273
Goodnight.

206
00:14:33,273 --> 00:14:36,076
(laughing)

207
00:14:46,086 --> 00:14:47,420
- "Dear Derek.

208
00:14:47,420 --> 00:14:50,023
All well, road clear,
 come immediately."

209
00:14:50,023 --> 00:14:52,993
Okay.

210
00:14:52,993 --> 00:14:55,428
Motel Hilton.

211
00:15:02,802 --> 00:15:06,706
(dramatic music)

212
00:15:33,700 --> 00:15:35,502
(lightning strikes)

213
00:15:35,502 --> 00:15:38,938
(dramatic music)

214
00:15:45,545 --> 00:15:48,415
(groaning)

215
00:15:57,457 --> 00:16:00,393
(screaming)

216
00:16:00,393 --> 00:16:04,164
(dramatic music)

217
00:17:04,057 --> 00:17:05,258
- "Dear, Derek.

218
00:17:05,258 --> 00:17:07,460
All well, road clear,
 come immediately."

219
00:17:07,460 --> 00:17:09,629
What does it mean?

220
00:17:09,629 --> 00:17:12,799
And who's Derek?

221
00:17:12,799 --> 00:17:14,167
(laughing)

222
00:17:14,167 --> 00:17:18,438
- [Colin] Oh well, that's funny.

223
00:17:18,438 --> 00:17:20,006
- Who's Derek?

224
00:17:20,006 --> 00:17:22,175
Doesn't ring any bells.

225
00:17:22,175 --> 00:17:24,844
Unless possibly it's--

226
00:17:24,844 --> 00:17:28,281
- Who?

227
00:17:28,281 --> 00:17:29,649
- No one.

228
00:17:29,649 --> 00:17:31,118
Just a stupid thought.

229
00:17:31,118 --> 00:17:32,652
(laughing)

230
00:17:32,652 --> 00:17:35,021
- Let Kiki devour
 it, he loves paper.

231
00:17:35,021 --> 00:17:36,089
He's neglected.

232
00:17:36,089 --> 00:17:39,092
(laughing)

233
00:17:41,194 --> 00:17:43,029
- No it's going
 to be sent to him.

234
00:17:43,029 --> 00:17:46,065
It's the best thing.

235
00:17:48,501 --> 00:17:51,738
This Derek knows
 that Michel was here.

236
00:17:51,738 --> 00:17:56,008
And if he gets Michel's note,
 he won't get suspicious.

237
00:17:56,008 --> 00:17:59,779
And he'll pop right down,
 and we'll clear this all up.

238
00:17:59,779 --> 00:18:02,615
All up.

239
00:18:05,718 --> 00:18:07,920
- Another order for
 soaps heads, hmm?

240
00:18:07,920 --> 00:18:10,857
I'll mail it.

241
00:18:25,004 --> 00:18:27,907
(bird calls)

242
00:18:43,890 --> 00:18:44,991
- Ah.

243
00:18:44,991 --> 00:18:47,727
Hi there, you mothers.

244
00:18:48,661 --> 00:18:49,462
(laughing)

245
00:18:49,462 --> 00:18:51,531
You want some too?

246
00:18:51,531 --> 00:18:54,701
Yeah great bastards.

247
00:18:54,701 --> 00:18:58,838
(bird calls)

248
00:18:58,838 --> 00:19:02,942
(clock chiming)

249
00:19:10,983 --> 00:19:12,819
Anyone home?

250
00:19:12,819 --> 00:19:16,456
(dramatic music)

251
00:19:56,263 --> 00:19:59,699
(whistling)

252
00:19:59,699 --> 00:20:03,270
(dramatic music)

253
00:20:14,914 --> 00:20:17,049
- Who are you?

254
00:20:17,049 --> 00:20:19,118
- You the boss lady here?

255
00:20:19,118 --> 00:20:20,186
- I asked first.

256
00:20:20,186 --> 00:20:21,788
- Cigarette?

257
00:20:21,788 --> 00:20:22,922
- Well?

258
00:20:22,922 --> 00:20:26,359
- Name's Alex, Alex Borland.

259
00:20:26,359 --> 00:20:27,594
Mm-mm.

260
00:20:27,594 --> 00:20:29,462
Hey Michel wasn't kidding.

261
00:20:29,462 --> 00:20:31,264
This is one beautiful villa.

262
00:20:31,264 --> 00:20:32,799
By the way, where is Michel?

263
00:20:32,799 --> 00:20:35,635
He said to come here at 10:30
 and here he is standing me up.

264
00:20:35,635 --> 00:20:37,203
Where are you hiding him?

265
00:20:37,203 --> 00:20:40,840
In your bed?

266
00:20:40,840 --> 00:20:43,175
- What are you talking about?

267
00:20:43,175 --> 00:20:45,378
- About Michel.

268
00:20:45,378 --> 00:20:47,747
And about his dog.

269
00:20:47,747 --> 00:20:51,751
This is Buck's collar.

270
00:20:52,919 --> 00:20:54,387
Look if Michel
 and I are friends,

271
00:20:54,387 --> 00:20:56,489
and Michel is your
 cousin, the two of us

272
00:20:56,489 --> 00:21:00,327
can be open with
 each other, can't we?

273
00:21:00,327 --> 00:21:01,961
- I suppose so.

274
00:21:01,961 --> 00:21:05,031
Michel received a
 call from London.

275
00:21:05,031 --> 00:21:06,999
- An emergency,
